>>35087822
As one Anon pointed out, cyclical menstruation is a very rare phenomenon in modern biology that is exclusive to mammals, and mostly prevalent in primates, which is no surprise, I'm sure. Animals that menstruate shed recurrently generated uterine lining that's discarded after ovulation, along with unfertilized eggs, which incubate within the womb if fertilization occurs. Aves don't menstruate because there's no uterine lining to shed - the egg serves as both gamete and incubatory vehicle.
Ovulation can be as recurrent in anthro hens as you want it to be, but take care not to place them on cycles matching that of feral aves; I can't imagine a humanoid creature living under that kind of physical stress, to say nothing of how much food she'd need to maintain her calcium levels. Fitting for a smol creature with hollow bones.
Also consider what ovulation entails, and what social norms might form around them. Some birds lay recurrently and often, others cycle through seasons (common in large species of birds and reptiles), periods of time when they're horny and laying eggs at moments of peak arousal (climax). This will obviously be a strange time to try and satisfy your waifeather's need if you aren't ready to take on the responsibility of half a dozen or so ultra-floofy, noisy chicks, all clamoring for your love, affection, and frequent snacks. Anonymous Wed 30 Dec 2020 14:27:22 No.35111259 Report
Quoted By: >>35111373 >>35117688
>>35111014
In an "ideal" way?
Probably gradually going back and forth between making physical changes to their body followed by mental changes that allow them to make use of their altered body in a way that feels natural and normal for them. Some jumps would still happen though, like making them walk upright and changing their eyes to face forward. Make their lifespans longer. Stick them upright, get them used to walking like that, make their legs longer following the initial line. Make their hands more capable and make them able to still have use of their hands. Then make their body closer in size to humans, again, making it bigger or smaller in gradual steps. After the physical stuff is worked out and they can go about their daily activities without issue then we make changes to stuff like their diet to allow them to be fed the same things as humans. At that same stage we could also go about removing the most troublesome behavioral things in them like female bunnies randomly eating their children, lionesses killing their children of another mate, and generally things like instinctual urges to kill certain other species. Then go about changing their vocal chords and other related things to allow them as close to human speech as possible when they eventually learn it. If at all possible allow for interbreeding without hybridization. I'm probably missing something else, but after that is all done then we could go about making them smarter and giving them sapience.
In what way is most likely to happen?
Probably along the lines of equivalent to a person being trapped in an animal body with no way to properly communicate to us that they have sapience, forever being treated as nothing more than just an especially clever animal.
